{"author":{"id":"cff9ab1d2ee9741039b2a60d90cca378a5320ba753398f6f3df8d03abcebee1b"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1772618846,"nonce":"PJ2qwhcTKMQqtvRa2fgirS+Lh7E=","title":"refactor: deploy script self-overwrite problem","message":"## Problem\n\nThe deploy script downloads itself from the target branch, which can overwrite itself with an older version. This causes a chicken-and-egg problem: running `./deploy.sh beta` with an old script on the server pulls from main (ignoring the argument), then overwrites itself back to the old version.\n\n## Options\n\n1. **Stop self-updating**: Remove the deploy.sh download line. The script is server infrastructure that doesn't change per branch. Update manually via scp when needed.\n\n2. **Use git sparse checkout**: Replace curl-based downloads with a shallow git clone. Atomic, consistent, no token needed with SSH keys, no self-overwrite. Example approach:\n\n```bash\ntmp=$(mktemp -d)\ngit clone --depth 1 --branch \"$BRANCH\" --sparse \"$REPO\" \"$tmp\"\nfor f in $FILES; do cp \"$tmp/$f\" \"$DEPLOY_DIR/$f\"; done\nrm -rf \"$tmp\"\n```\n\nOption 2 is cleaner long-term.","files":null}]}